      <text>Conics-1-tangents and normals - random</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the equations of the tangent and normal to the circle \[ {@q@}\] at the point \(({@ap@},{@bp@})\).</p>
<p>Tangent: [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>
<p><span>Normal: [[input:ans2]] </span><span>[[validation:ans2]]<span><br /></span></span></p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Tangents:</strong> Circles are a special case of the ellipse centred at \((x_c,y_c)\)<br />\[ \frac{(x-x_c)^2}{a^2}+\frac{(y-y_c)^2}{b^2}=1.\]<br />The tangent to this ellipse, through the point \((x',y')\), is given by<br />\[ \frac{(x-x_c)(x'-x_c)}{a^2}+\frac{(y-y_c)(y'-y_c)}{b^2}=1.\]<br />In our case we have \(a^2=b^2={@rs@}\) and the equation of our circle is \[ {@p@}\]  Using \(x'={@ap@}\) and \(y'={@bp@}\) we have the tangent line as \[ {@(x-ac)*(ap-ac)+(y-bc)*(bp-bc)=rs@}\] Expanding and rearranging give \[ {@expand(tas1)@}\]</p>
<p><strong>Normals:</strong> A line through \((x',y')\) with gradient \(m\) has equation \[ y=m(x-x')+y'.\] If a line has gradient \(m\) then the perpendicular line has gradient \(-1/m\). Our tangent line has gradient {@pm@}, so the normal line through \(({@ap@},{@bp@})\) has equation \[ y= {@tas2@} = {@expand(tas2)@}.\]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
